p2
VGrand music fest
p3
sVnews
p4
VThe festival commenced with a vocal concert by the students of Gayathri Music School, Thillainagar. A group of boys and girls, all below seven years,  rendered songs on Lord Ganapati, Lord Muruga, Lord Siva and  Ambal.This was  followed by another group vocal presentation  by  Ranjitha, Madumitha and Susi Priya. Next came the trio,  Anurekha, Revathi and Sneha,  who rendered kirtanas of Tyagaraja, Purandaradasa and  Papanasam Sivan  with total perfection. All the three groups were ably supported by Ramji on the violin and Vijayaragavan on the mridangam.Sunitha&#8217;s troupe from  Anna Nagar, comprising six young students, presented the second day&#8217;s programme. Deepa Rajagopal of Thillainagar and Priyanka Raghavan, a class IX student of Mahatma Gandhi Centenary Vidyalaya, presented enchanting concerts on the next two days. Nagercoil Ganapathi played the violin and V. Swaminathan played the mridangam.On the fifth day, Valarpirai Gayathri, a B.E. bio-technology student of SASTRA University, Thanjavur, presented  devotional songs. She was supported by Lakshmi Narayanan on the violin and Ranganathan on the mridangam.K. Sindhuja and N. Aiswarya&#8217;s  concert was the highlight of the penultimate day&#8217;s programme. Sindhuja, a final year BCA student of the Holy Cross College and Aiswarya, a plus two student of St. John&#8217;s Vestry Anglo-Indian Higher Secondary School, commenced the concert with &#8216;Jaya Jaya Swami Jaya Jaya,&#8217; a Narayana Tirtha tarangam in Nattai.   While Kamalahasan supported them on the violin, Venkatesh Babu supported them on the mridangam.The festival came to a close on September 21 with a gala performance by Uma Sakthivel and Sathya Ravi.According to the Principal of  Gayathri Music School, V. Sankari, the festival was organised to identify and recognise the talent of local artistes.All the performers were either present or former students of the school.
